### Analytic Reporter Web Directory Tree
Analytic Reporter Web application is composed by the following set of directories as follow:

AnalyticReporterWebServer
|--- scripts
|    |--- pythoninstall.sh
|--- source
|    |--- templates
|    |    |--- login.html
|    |    |--- generate_report.html
|    |--- mongo
|    |    |--- mongolib.py
|    |--- analyticReporterWebServer.py
|    |--- AnalyticReporterWebServer.conf
|--- python_requirements
|--- README



### Analytic Reporter Web Software requirements
ARWS can run on any platform (Windowsm, Linux, MacOS) if the following software requirements are satisfied:
	* Python 3.8 and Python packages:
		* PyMongo
		* XlsWriter
		* DateTime
		* Flask
		* flask-cors
		* pyopenssl
Such requirements can be installed easily by following the instructions contained into 'Install Analytic Reporter software requirements' section of this REAMDE.

ARWC needs only a Web browser (Firefox, Chrome, IE, ...) in order to be executed and doesn't need any additional requirements.

## Getting Started
In order to start using Analytic Reporter Web you need to:

	* Download the Analytic Reporter Web
	* Install ARWS software requirements
	* Configure the ARWS
	* Launch the ARWS
	* Connect to ARWS

### Download Analytic Reporter Web
In order to download Analytic Reporter application use the following command:

	```
		git clone https://github.com/giuseppe-pedone/AnalyticReporterWeb.git
	```

### Install Analytic Reporter Web Server software requirements
Once downloaded the Analytic Reporter Web, in order to satisfy ARWS software requirements:

* Install Python and Python system requirements by running on Linux ./scripts/pythoninstall.sh from ROOT directory:
  
  ```
  	sudo ./scripts/pythoninstall.sh
  
  ```

  on other platforms (Windows, MacOS) install manually Python3.8 and the following python packages (PyMongo, XlsWriter, DateTime, Flask, flask-cors)

### Configure Analytic Reporter Web Server application

To configure ARWS correctly you need to modify the AnalyticReporter.conf file contained into AnalyticReporterWebServer directory.
It is a JSON document that contains all possible ARWS settings:

	* mongoDatabaseName is the ID name of the mongodb database from which getting data (string)
	* mongoCollectionName is the ID name of the mongodb collection from which getting data (string)
	* mongoServerIP represents the IP address to use for mongodb connection, so the same IP where MongoDB server is running (string)
	* mongoServerPort represents the TCP address to use for mongodb connection, so the same port where MongoDB server is running (int)
	* analyticReporterWebServerIP represents the IP on which ARWS performs the binding (string)
	* analyticReporterWebServerPort represents the PORT on which ARWS is listening to (int)
	* analyticReporterWebServerLogDirectory: represents the directory path to store logs (string)
	* analyticReporterWebServerLogFilename: represents the current log filename (string)
	* analyticReporterWebServerMinimumLogLevel: represents the minimum log level of the server (string, possible values: DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL)
	* analyticReporterWebServerMaximumLogFileSizeInMB: represents the maximum size of a log file in MegaBytes (int)
	* analyticReporterWebServerMaximumNumberOfLogFiles: represent the maximum number of log files to maintain (int)
	* analyticReporterWebServerName: represents the Web Server name (string)
	* analyticReporterWebServerInDebugMode : specifies if running the Web Server in debug mode or not (boolean, possible values: true, false)
	* analyticReporterWebServerPassword: specifies the authentication password on login (string)
	* analyticReporterWebServerSessionLifetimeSeconds: specifies the duration, in seconds, of the HTTPS session (int)  
	* analyticReporterWebServerReportableApplications: specifies which applications are available for analytic reporting (string array) - current default set is [ "Predicts-v0", "Predicts-v1" ]

### Launch Analytic Reporter Web Server
* Launching ARWS by running directly python with the following command, from AnalyticReporterWebServer/source directory:
  
  ```
  	sudo python3.8 ./analyticReporterWebServer.py
  
  ```

Notes: It is supposed that the Analytic Reporter configuration file is named AnalyticReporter.conf and it is located into AnalyticReporterWebServer/source directory.

### Connect to Analytic Reporter Web Server
* In order to connect to ARWS use a simple browser and type the https url of the ARWS for example https://servername or https://serverip